SIMPLE: strength
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Strength
<hw>Strength</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>strengthe</ets>, AS. <ets>streng⟦edh⟧u</ets>, fr. <ets>strang</ets>
strong. See <er>Strong</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or
state of being strong; ability to do or to bear; capacity for exertion
or endurance, whether physical, intellectual, or moral; force; vigor;
power; <as>as, <ex>strength</ex> of body or of the arm;
<ex>strength</ex> of mind, of memory, or of judgment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All his [Samson's] <qex>strength</qex> in his hairs were.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou must outlive⟦br⟧
Thy youth, thy <qex>strength</qex>, thy beauty.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Power to resist force; solidity or toughness; the
quality of bodies by which they endure the application of force without
breaking or yielding; -- in this sense opposed to
<contr>frangibility</contr>; <as>as, the <ex>strength</ex> of a bone, of
a beam, of a wall, a rope, and the like</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The brittle
<xex>strength</xex> of bones.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Power of resisting attacks; impregnability.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Our castle's <xex>strength</xex> will laugh a siege to
scorn.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That quality which tends to secure results;
effective power in an institution or enactment; security; validity;
legal or moral force; logical conclusiveness; <as>as, the
<ex>strength</ex> of social or legal obligations; the <ex>strength</ex>
of law; the <ex>strength</ex> of public opinion; <ex>strength</ex> of
evidence; <ex>strength</ex> of argument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, is regarded as embodying or
affording force, strength, or firmness; that on which confidence or
reliance is based; support; security.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God is our refuge and <qex>strength</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xlvi.
1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What they boded would be a mischief to us, you are providing shall
be one of our principal <qex>strengths</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sprat.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Certainly there is not a greater <qex>strength</qex> against
temptation.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Force as measured; amount, numbers, or power of any
body, as of an army, a navy, and the like; as, what is the
<xex>strength</xex> of the enemy by land, or by sea?</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Vigor or style; force of expression; nervous
diction; -- said of literary work.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And praise the easy vigor of a life⟦br⟧
Where Denham's <qex>strength</qex> and Waller's sweetness join.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Intensity; -- said of light or color.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bright Phoebus in his <qex>strength</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Intensity or degree of the distinguishing and
essential element; spirit; virtue; excellence; -- said of liquors,
solutions, etc.; <as>as, the <ex>strength</ex> of wine or of
acids</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A strong place; a stronghold.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>On the strength of</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Upon the strength of</b></col></mcol>, <cd>in reliance
upon.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The allies, after a successful summer, are too apt,
<xex>upon the strength of</xex> it, to neglect their preparations for
the ensuing campaign.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Force; robustness; toughness; hardness;
stoutness; brawniness; lustiness; firmness; puissance; support; spirit;
validity; authority. See <er>Force</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strength</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Strength
<hw>Strength</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To strengthen.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strengthen</ent>⟦br⟧
